## 1. Access your Google Cloud Platform account

Log in to your Google Cloud Platform account. If you don't have an account, Google is offering a [60-day free trial](https://cloud.google.com/compute/) for up to $300 (USD) of usage.

If you are unable to use Google Cloud Platform, you can [try a different option](/modules/learn-the-basics/ubuntu/) for this module.

[END_BOX]

[START_BOX]

## 2. Launch an Ubuntu 14.04 instance

Next, bring up an Ubuntu instance on Compute Engine.

If you're new to Google Cloud Platform, Google's [Quickstart Using a Linux VM](https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/quickstart-linux) tutorial walks you through the creation of your first Linux virtual machine.

[COMMENT] This module refers to the Google Cloud Platform Console documentation to help you manage your virtual machine. Google also provides a [command-line interface](https://cloud.google.com/compute/docs/gcloud-compute/) (CLI).

When you're ready to continue with this module, bring up a standard **Ubuntu 14.04 LTS** system.

When you choose the machine type, select **micro**, **small**, or **1 vCPU**. **micro** instances cost less, but **small** or **1 vCPU** will give you better performance.

When you choose the firewall settings, select **Allow HTTP traffic** and **Allow HTTPS traffic**. This ensures your system is connectable on ports 22 (SSH), 80 (HTTP), and 443 (HTTPS).

[COMMENT] Technically, port 443 is not required for this module. But setting up that port now prepares you for the next module, where you'll configure your server to be managed remotely.

[END_BOX]

